 in order to apprehend death as a collective, multispecies event. Sister Death proposes an alternative view in which life and death are not mortal enemies destined for mutual destruction. Instead, they are engaged in a contested, tense, and sometimes mutually empowering form of connection—a sisterhood.Eloquent and approachable, this book deftly integrates the insights of a number of disciplines to provide a profound reconsideration of the relations between life and death. Sister Death also features a series of original works by the artist Krista Dragomer that stage an ongoing conceptual conversation with the text.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aDeathxPolitical aspects. 0aDeathxReligious aspects. 0aPolitical theology. 7aRELIGION / Religion, Politics & State.2bisacsh  aChristian political theology.  aJacques Derrida.  aKrista Dragomer.  aSaint Francis of Assisi.  aSister Death.  aToni Morrison.  acontinental philosophy.  acritical life studies.  acritical race theory.  adeath and dying.  adeath positivity.  aenvironmental humanities.  alife and death.  amortality studies.  amortality.  apsychoanalysis.  areligious philosophy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074967040uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/maro2083640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231557399423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231557399/original  a978-3-11-074967-0  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK